snippet.textDisplay: From Tribune Karachi: As the only Indian female singer to be the lead vocalist of a popular Pakistani act, Chatterjee confessed it was a dreamlike experience and thanked Mekaal for the opportunity. “People of the subcontinent would know that an Indo-Pak collaboration is the most difficult thing, given the current times. But I am glad it happened, thanks to Mekaal and his effort to venture into something worthwhile in music,” she told The Express Tribune.She believed that she fit in with the band’s style of music. “I felt the music of the band was tailor made for me and my sensibilities as an artist. I had training in Indian Classical music and that definitely helped,” Chatterjee added. “But I had to work hard on the language, especially Punjabi and Persian, since I never sang in these languages before. Also, the compositions are often challenging which is my great point of interest.”Apart from her experience in playback singing in Bollywood, Chatterjee has also trained in Indian classical music. With her ever-increasing exposure to different genres, she has tried to incorporate the world folk styles of Africa, South Eastern Europe and Flamenco among others, into her performances.

snippet.textDisplay: Sharmistha Chatterjee is a Hindustani Classical , Bollywood , World Folk , Fusion , R&B , Soul , Jazz , Progressive singer. She has given her voice in "Paas Aaya Kyun" from the movie "Aggar", Voice behind popular commercials such as "Magic of Frooti- SRK" , "Set Wet - Buri Nazar Wale/ Call of the cool "7Up" etc. Sharmistha Chatterjee is a lead vocalist at Louiz Banks Ganga Shakti, Ranjit Barot & The Resistance, and Mekaal Hasan Band. Here she sings Bullhe Shah's famous Kaafi in Raag Bhiarvi in exquisite clarity and style. It is a difficult composition and she has done a wonderful job at her effortless classical singing.

snippet.textDisplay: Something strange with the Gujrat City surroundings and its culture which has historically been so romantic and violent as well. Heer/Ranjha is one romantic unsuccessful sad story  and another is Sohni/Mahiwal from the region. Even Alexander came and conquered this area but never went further into India because his soldiers refused to go any further. I just remembered (being born in Gujrat City) that my mother's cousin also was in love and wanted to get married to this girl but his father completely refused and was angry about it. The cousin said that both of them will go to the river and drown themselves. His father still refused. So, both went to the river but he jumped in and died while the girl came back.  Very sad romantic stories from the region. Even my father eloped with a rich neighborhood girl but came back after two days. He, somehow, married my mother after a while and that girl died soon after a year or two.  I am 73 now but could not get the full story from my father while he was alive. What a violent and romantic area of Indian sub continent and I am now living so far far away from it.
